ing the period from 1870 to 1940, chronicling one generation's suspicions toward public education and another's need to assimilate.Through careful research Lassonde finds that not all working class parents were enthusiastic supporters of education. Not only did the time and energy spent in school restrict children's potential financial contributions to the family, but attitudes that children encountered in school often ran counter to the family's traditional values. Legally mandated education and child labor laws eventually resolved these conflicts, but not without considerable reluctance and resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHome and schoolxHistoryx19th centuryxConnecticutxNew Haven. 0aHome and schoolxHistoryx20th centuryxConnecticutxNew Haven. 0aHome and schoolzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistoryy19th century. 0aHome and schoolzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxEducationxHistoryx19th centuryxConnecticutxNew Haven. 0aImmigrantsxEducationxHistoryx20th centuryxConnecticutxNew Haven. 0aImmigrantsxEducationzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrantsxEducationzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalian American childrenxEducationxHistoryx19th centuryxNew Haven. 0aItalian American childrenxEducationxHistoryx20th centuryxNew Haven. 0aItalian American childrenxEducationzNew HavenxHistoryy19th century. 0aItalian American childrenxEducationzNew HavenxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classxEducationxHistoryx19th centuryxConnecticutxNew Haven. 0aWorking classxEducationxHistoryx20th centuryxConnecticutxNew Haven. 0aWorking classxEducationzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classxEducationzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisac